It is nothing more or less than a didactic poem on the art of love, which appeared in three books in 2 or 1 B. c. under the name of Ars Amatoria. ln the first two books he drills men in the various, sometimes extremely dubious artS, by the practise of which they may hope to attain success in loveÍ¾ in the third he addresses his instruction to women. The poem shows a chaos of petty details as systematically organized as if they were parts of a scientific treatise. Current modes and methods ol love- making are described with such vividness, such apparent mastery ol the subject, that we are forced to assume that it was a field in which the poet himself bad had no incon- siderable experieuce. As a sort of palinode to the Ars Amatoria he wrote another poem, Remedia Amoris. This also is didactic in tone, pointing out possible remedies for love, showing how one finding himself in love can win freedom once more. Between the composition of the Ars Amatoria and that of the Remedia Amoris the poem entitled M edicamirra Facier' is probably to be placed.

The poems which have been mentioned form the first group of Ovid's literary productioris, The second consists of two works of much wider scope and more serious pre- tensions. These are the Metamorphoses and the Fasti. In the former, which consists of fifteen books, a very long series of myths of transformation have been welded into a seemingly organic wholeÍ¾ in the latter we bave a poetical version of the Roman calendar, with descriptions of the various festivals and speculations as to their origin. The greater part of the material of the Metamorphoses has been drawn from Greek mythology, but in the latter part of the work, where the poet deals with Roman legendS, a decidedly patriotic element may be noticed.
